{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01G1eeUaGMfXwesPEcibL3HX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the socket is at `/var/run/postgresql/.s.PGSQL.5432`. For the `postgres` npm package, I can use a connection URL with the socket host. The postgres npm package supports socket connections. Let me check how to use it.\n\nFor the `postgres` npm package, to connect via Unix socket, you can use:\n```\npostgres(\"postgres://vscode@localhost/rng_utopia_dev\", { host: \"/var/run/postgresql\" })\n```\n\nOr use the URL format: `postgresql://vscode@/rng_utopia_dev?host=/var/run/postgresql`\n\nLet me check how the existing tests handle this... The existing tests use `postgresql://vscode@localhost:5432/rng_utopia_dev` which also fails on TCP. \n\nHmm, but the tests supposedly pass, so maybe Postgres is listening on TCP as well or there's something else going on. Looking at the test output though, all 8 tests are failing with ECONNREFUSED, which is strange if the existing tests in `src/__tests__/` have been working. Let me trace back through the history — iteration 1 actually notes that TCP connections have always been problematic since the dev Postgres only listens on Unix socket, and they've been verifying SQL directly with psql instead.\n\nSo rather than trying to enable TCP, I should just switch to using the Unix socket approach. The postgres npm package supports Unix sockets through the `host` option in the connection URL, so I'll update the test configuration to connect that way instead.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":458,"cache_read_input_tokens":50830,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":458},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5a06e2aa-bee3-40eb-a97d-65518436146f","uuid":"7